The Myothian Falcon

Andy Joel

 - - - That day, the 9th of June, 3145, started out like any other, perhaps a little hotter than usual. Then Maisy DeValle entered his office.

Vic's office

 - - - Vic Gantry's office was small, but he tried to keep it smart. In the centre of the room, there was a neo-chrome desk, with a computer screen on it, and a black chair behind it. Behind the chair, a window, looking out on New Chicago. On the north wall there was a picture of a gazelle, the door was to the west. There were also two chairs for clients to sit on, and at the moment an attractive woman, hopefully a new client, was sat on the left one, waiting for Vic to ask her what her business was.
> ask maisy about business

 - - - "So what can I do you for?" asked Vic.

 - - - "I need your help, Mr Gantry," she said "My husband... oh, it is too terrible... My husband's dead, and the police think I did it! You've got to help me."
> ask maisy about money

 - - - "Okay, lady, I'll take the case. It'll cost you 1000 credits, and I'll need 500 in advance to cover expenses."

 - - - "That's fine, Mr Gantry. I am not without means. I'll pay you an additional 500 credits if you can clear my name within two days." She handed over her credit chip, and let Vic take off 500 credits. "I'll be at the Grand Hotel if you need to contact me; I'll be booked in as Leona Jones."
> w

The Office Lobby

 - - - The lobby was clean and functional. To the south, the sounds of the street drifted in though the large glass doors; to the north, a notice board directed people to the various businesses in the building. Vic's office was to the east.
> read sign

 - - - The notice listed the businesses in the building. "Vic Gantry, P.I." was seventh, under "Linda, Love Massages". Vic glanced at Linda's door, to the northwest, wondering about those massages...
> nw

Linda Love's Office

 - - - This was similar to Vic's office in size, though without a window. Linda was sat at a retro pine desk, and as Vic entered the room, she took a break from typing at her computer, and looked him up and down.
> look at linda love

 - - - Dressed in black trousers, and a pale blue shirt, Linda Love looked to be in her mid-twenties. Her blonde hair was cropped short, and she smelt of cheap perfume. She looked questioningly at Vic as she sat behind her desk.
> ask linda about massages

 - - - "That dumb sign," signed Linda. "My company offers secure messaging, using 2k-bit encryption over standard internet protocols. My name is Linda Love, so 'Linda Love, Messages.' You wouldn't believe the sort of dirty old men I get coming in here thinking I... Well, anyway. You're the guy from across the lobby, aren't you?"
> ask linda about encryption

 - - - "If I had a little problem with some encrypted files, you'd be able to help me I guess."

 - - - Linda shook her head. "Technically I might be able to, but it's against the law. So no."
> ask linda about date

 - - - "Say, I was wondering...," said Vic, "perhaps you and I could hook up some time?"

 - - - "You mean like a date? Sure, might be kind of fun. I don't really know many guys since moving to this part of town. Say, we could go to the fancy French place across the road. L'Escargo's. I'll book us a table for this evening."
> se

The Office Lobby

 - - - The lobby was clean and functional. To the south, the sounds of the street drifted in though the large glass doors; to the north, a notice board directed people to the various businesses in the building. Vic's office was to the east.
> s

Yardley Street (East)

 - - - Yardley Street was one of the busier thoroughfares in the New Chicago central business district, running east to west. A constant stream of people, both humans and occasional Uralgans, and even a few more exotic races, headed in either direction. To the north was Derrington Building, where Vic had his office, to the south, Renoir building, and "Bert's Bagels", where Vic would usually grab lunch. There was not much to the east, but heading west might be good, thought Vic.
> w

Yardley Street

 - - - Vic was now in the middle of Yardley Street, near the transit station, which was on the south side of the street. Shops and other businesses lined the street. Numerous people were out, hurrying about their business, or just enjoying the fine weather.

 - - - An AutoClean hummed to itself as it scrubbed the pavements.
> s

 - - - The TeleMat system offered instant transportation to any other TeleMat station in the city. For 5 credits, the system would annihilate your body, transmit the data to a destination booth, and create your body anew. Vic contemplated where to go. The DeValle mansion on Opulent Street seemed a good idea, but it might be worth talking to Detective Munroe; she would probably be in Donegal's on Bureau Street.

Yardley Street TeleMat Station

 - - - Vic looked about Yardley Street Telemat Station. It was typical of many such stations across New Chicago. Larger than most, it had twenty four booths along three walls; fourteen were for departing, ten for arriving. As he wondered where to go next, a stream of people passed through.
> teleport
Choose a destination
 - Opulent Boulevard

 - - - Vic typed in the code for his destination, and an instant later was in a booth at Opulent Boulevard.

Opulent Boulevard TeleMat Station

 - - - Vic was stood on the concourse at Opulent Boulevard transit. It was noticeably cleaner than most, and quiet too. Not only were fewer people using the booths, but there was little noise coming from the street. The usual hum of city was muted here.
> n

Opulent Boulevard

 - - - Originally named after Jackie O'Poole, one of the original settlers, the name Opulent Boulevard became popular as more and more of the city's ultra-rich moved here. Opulent Boulevard ran some way out of the city into the Uralgan jungle - far enough to allow the residents to feel removed from the common man, but still close enough to the safety of the city. The road was quiet; Vic could see no one for several blocks. Both sides were lined with jacaranda trees, and behind them the high walls surrounded the various mansions. The DeValle mansion was off to the east.

 - - - A native Uralgan bird, something like a parrot, cocked its head as it watched Vic from its perch high in a tree.
> e

Opulent Boulevard (East)

 - - - Vic stood opposite the gates to the DeValle mansion. A cop stood at the entrance, so getting inside might not be easy. Through the gates, Vic could see a long driveway, presumably heading up to the house.

 - - - A sudden gust of wind caused a flurry of blue blossom to fall from the jacaranda trees.
> ask cop about maisy

 - - - Vic sauntered over to the gate, and nodded at the cop. "Hey, it's Mister Gantry, isn't it? How are you doing sir?"

 - - - "I was just idling wondering if you know anything about Maisy DeValle, Harry."

 - - - "I know she murdered her husband. We'll have her soon, too. You can't get far in this city without being traced. The guys at the station'll be checking the TeleMat logs even as we speak."
> ask cop about telemat logs

 - - - "What's that about TeleMat logs, Harry? Who has access to them?"

 - - - "The detectives back at the station, though they need a judge to agree it."
> e

Opulent Boulevard (Further East)

 - - - This was the end of Opulent Boulevard. To the east, the gates to the mansions of another wealthy citizen of New Chicago, to the north and south, the high walls to keep the less wealthy citizens out.

 - - - A squirrel, startled by Vic's approach, ran across the road, and up a nearby tree. Vic wondered if he could climb it too, and see over the wall.
> climb

 - - - It was a few years since Vic had last climbed a tree, but with some effort he hauled himself up.

Opulent Boulevard (Further East; Up a Tree)

 - - - From the tree, Vic had a great view up and down the street. He was higher than the wall here, so he could also see the DeValle mansion, the curving form that was so popular a couple of centuries ago. With a bit of effort, he thought he could jump across on to the wall to the north. Otherwise, he was going to have to climb down again.
> jump

 - - - After a moment's hesitation, Vic leapt across on to the wall

DeValle Mansion (on the Wall)

 - - - The wall around the DeValle mansion was lined with vicious spikes for the most part, but over the years they had become rusted and broken. Where Vic stood a whole section was missing, giving him a more-or-less flat, if narrow, platform to stand on. The gardens below him were large by New Chicago standards. With the Uralgans declared an intelligent species, further expansion became a legal nightmare, and the humans on Uralga IV had been getting more and more densely populated ever since.

 - - - It looked as though someone else had made use of it recently, too. Vic noticed a cigarette end and matchbook lying where they had been discarded. The previous caller had stopped to have a smoke here, perhaps as he or she watched the house.
> get matchbook

 - - - Vic picked up the match book .
> look at matchbook

 - - - Vic turned the match book over. All the matches were gone, but the image on the front indicated it came from the Lion's Den. That was a dive on Twenty Third Avenue that Vic knew only too well.
> get cigarette end

 - - - Vic carefully picked up the cigarette end, and placed it into an evidence bag. There were all sorts of stories a used cigarette could tell to the forensics guys, if he handed it to Detective Munroe.
> d

DeValle Mansion (Side Garden)

 - - - Vic stood in amongst some shrubs, near the wall. It looked easy enough to get back up on top of the wall from here. The lawn was well-kept, good enough for playing golf on, if a guy was so inclined. Trees and shrubs along the sides shielded the high walls. Vic spotted a couple of security cameras mounted on posts.

 - - - The house was to the northwest, built in the Duro style that had been popular in the twenty-ninth century; a series of cylinders that seems to flow into each other. The central cylinder had the main entrance, a grand arched door with a cop on it. Vic would not be going in that way. On either side, shorter, but fatter cylinders for the various reception and bedrooms; that looked to be the study nearest to him, Vic thought. Was one window not quite shut properly?

 - - - The garden extended to the west, but northwards a high wall marked the boundary of the Uralgan jungle, beyond which Vic could see the indigenous trees of the planet.
> look at window

 - - - Vic had a closer look at the study window. Sure enough, it was not quite flush with its surround, and now he could see scratch marks, as though someone had forced the window with a crowbar. He could probably get in the same way, he reckoned.
> in

 - - - Vic propped the window open. Using a branch of a substantial bush to help him, he slipped though the window, into the study.

DeValle Mansion (Study)

 - - - Lawrence DeValle's study. Vic knocked on the large desk. Real wood, and by the look of it, oak, imported from Earth. The desk alone was probably worth more than he made in a year. A matching chair, covered in dark leather, where Lawrence Devalle would sit. There were four more chairs, expensive, but not so comfortable, set in pairs against the walls. Two whole sides of the room were lined with books. As far as Vic could see there was only one reason to own a book, and that was to show off how much money you had to waste. There was a door to the west, and he could otherwise go back out the window.
> look at desk

 - - - Vic examined the desk more closely. Large, and rectangular, ornately carved, with drawers on the right. He realised there was a computer built into it; the screen and keyboard neatly tucked away. The computer was locked, and it was beyond Vic's skills to unlock it.
> open desk

 - - - Vic opened the desk.

 - - - It contained a Data Key.
> get data key

 - - - Vic picked up the data key .
> use data key

 - - - Bingo! With this data key Vic could get into the computer. Pretty lax of Lawrence DeValle to leave it lying around. Vic pushed it into the computer's socket. "Damn," he muttered. He had complete access to the files, but every one of them was encrypted. While he was in, he changed the security profile to allow remote access; now if he could only find someone who knew about hacking encrypted files...
> w

DeValle Mansion (Great Hall)

 - - - This was a large room, panelled in dark wood, dominated by a grand staircase, rising to the upper story. The staircase was carpeted in red, but the floor was tiled in an ornate geometric pattern. That would make cleaning the blood off easier, thought Vic ruefully. There was a lot of it. The body must have been taken already, and it was hard for Vic to tell anything from the white outline; for all he could tell, Lawrence DeValle had slipped and fallen down the stairs. There were doors to east and west, and rather larger, grander double doors to the north and south. The one to the south would be the front entrance, Vic reckoned. Along the wall there were a series of niches, each containing an odd statuette or other weird objet d'art. All but one, Vic noted.
> u

 - - - Vic headed up the wide staircase, careful to avoid the blood at the bottom. Portraits of the DeValle family stared down at him as he walked along the landing. The master bedroom was at the back; a huge circular bed, with black satin sheets. Walk-in wardrobes on either side, Lawrence's on the right, Maisy's on the left. A number of wigs; did Lawrence like dressing up in his wife's clothes? At the back, a large window giving a panoramic view of the Uralgan jungle. Rather more quickly Vic looked through the other rooms; smaller bedrooms, two bathrooms (both with gold fittings), before deciding there was nothing up there, and heading back down to the hall.
> look at niche

 - - - One niche was empty, but Vic saw a label there; something used to be there. He read the plaque: The Myothian Falcon. Ancient Uralgan artefact said to be the embodiment of the god of dreams, ca. 2840. Recovered by Dr George Lancing of the NCU, 3144.
> n

DeValle Mansion (Passage)

 - - - A wide passage way going the short distance from the hall, to the ball room. The floor was tiled with the same ornate pattern as the hall, the walls panelled in a darker wood.
> n

DeValle Mansion (Ballroom)

 - - - Now this was classy, Vic thought. It was a glass dome set down in the jungle. To the south, it was possible to make out the house through the trees; Vic could just about identify the master bedroom. The floor was wooden, but nevertheless felt soft and yielding. The only exit was south, back though the passage way. All around was the thick Uralgan forest, verdant and wild.
> look at jungle

 - - - Vic was a city boy at heart, but he could not resist the urge to just stare into the jungle for a few minutes. A scurry of movement to his right, as a rodent-like creature darted along a branch. A flash of colour as a bird or a butterfly or... Vic had no idea what, but it sure was beautiful.
> s

DeValle Mansion (Passage)

 - - - A wide passage way going the short distance from the hall, to the ball room. The floor was tiled with the same ornate pattern as the hall, the walls panelled in a darker wood.
> s

DeValle Mansion (Great Hall)

 - - - This was a large room, panelled in dark wood, dominated by a grand staircase, rising to the upper story. The staircase was carpeted in red, but the floor was tiled in an ornate geometric pattern. That would make cleaning the blood off easier, thought Vic ruefully. There was a lot of it. The body must have been taken already, and it was hard for Vic to tell anything from the white outline; for all he could tell, Lawrence DeValle had slipped and fallen down the stairs. There were doors to east and west, and rather larger, grander double doors to the north and south. The one to the south would be the front entrance, Vic reckoned. Along the wall there were a series of niches, each containing an odd statuette or other weird objet d'art. All but one, Vic noted.
> w

DeValle Mansion (Dining Room)

 - - - Vic could not help but be impressed with the style of the dining room. The dark wood table was almost large enough to play soccer on - though the oval shape would make it tricky. Eighteen chairs surrounded in in matching dark wood. On the west wall hung a large painting of Lawrence and Maisy DeValle.
> n

 - - - Vic headed into the kitchen, and the staff areas beyond, but it was soon apparent there was nothing much there. The housekeeper evidently lived elsewhere, and there were no personel effects or anything out of the ordinary. He went back to the dining room.
> e

DeValle Mansion (Great Hall)

 - - - This was a large room, panelled in dark wood, dominated by a grand staircase, rising to the upper story. The staircase was carpeted in red, but the floor was tiled in an ornate geometric pattern. That would make cleaning the blood off easier, thought Vic ruefully. There was a lot of it. The body must have been taken already, and it was hard for Vic to tell anything from the white outline; for all he could tell, Lawrence DeValle had slipped and fallen down the stairs. There were doors to east and west, and rather larger, grander double doors to the north and south. The one to the south would be the front entrance, Vic reckoned. Along the wall there were a series of niches, each containing an odd statuette or other weird objet d'art. All but one, Vic noted.
> e

DeValle Mansion (Study)

 - - - Lawrence DeValle's study. Vic knocked on the large desk. Real wood, and by the look of it, oak, imported from Earth. The desk alone was probably worth more than he made in a year. A matching chair, covered in dark leather, where Lawrence Devalle would sit. There were four more chairs, expensive, but not so comfortable, set in pairs against the walls. Two whole sides of the room were lined with books. As far as Vic could see there was only one reason to own a book, and that was to show off how much money you had to waste. There was a door to the west, and he could otherwise go back out the window.
> out

 - - - Vic climbed back out through the window, into the garden.

DeValle Mansion (Side Garden)

 - - - Vic stood in amongst some shrubs, near the wall. It looked easy enough to get back up on top of the wall from here. The lawn was well-kept, good enough for playing golf on, if a guy was so inclined. Trees and shrubs along the sides shielded the high walls. Vic spotted a couple of security cameras mounted on posts.

 - - - The house was to the northwest, built in the Duro style that had been popular in the twenty-ninth century; a series of cylinders that seems to flow into each other. The central cylinder had the main entrance, a grand arched door with a cop on it. Vic would not be going in that way. On either side, shorter, but fatter cylinders for the various reception and bedrooms; that looked to be the study nearest to him, Vic thought. Was one window not quite shut properly?

 - - - The garden extended to the west, but northwards a high wall marked the boundary of the Uralgan jungle, beyond which Vic could see the indigenous trees of the planet.
> u

DeValle Mansion (on the Wall)

 - - - The wall around the DeValle mansion was lined with vicious spikes for the most part, but over the years they had become rusted and broken. Where Vic stood a whole section was missing, giving him a more-or-less flat, if narrow, platform to stand on. The gardens below him were large by New Chicago standards. With the Uralgans declared an intelligent species, further expansion became a legal nightmare, and the humans on Uralga IV had been getting more and more densely populated ever since.
> s

 - - - Vic leapt from the wall on to a branch of the tree in the street.

Opulent Boulevard (Further East; Up a Tree)

 - - - From the tree, Vic had a great view up and down the street. He was higher than the wall here, so he could also see the DeValle mansion, the curving form that was so popular a couple of centuries ago. With a bit of effort, he thought he could jump across on to the wall to the north. Otherwise, he was going to have to climb down again.
> d

Opulent Boulevard (Further East)

 - - - This was the end of Opulent Boulevard. To the east, the gates to the mansions of another wealthy citizen of New Chicago, to the north and south, the high walls to keep the less wealthy citizens out.
> w

Opulent Boulevard (East)

 - - - Vic stood opposite the gates to the DeValle mansion. A cop stood at the entrance, so getting inside might not be easy. Through the gates, Vic could see a long driveway, presumably heading up to the house.
> w

Opulent Boulevard

 - - - Originally named after Jackie O'Poole, one of the original settlers, the name Opulent Boulevard became popular as more and more of the city's ultra-rich moved here. Opulent Boulevard ran some way out of the city into the Uralgan jungle - far enough to allow the residents to feel removed from the common man, but still close enough to the safety of the city. The road was quiet; Vic could see no one for several blocks. Both sides were lined with jacaranda trees, and behind them the high walls surrounded the various mansions. The DeValle mansion was off to the east.
> s

Opulent Boulevard TeleMat Station

 - - - Vic was stood on the concourse at Opulent Boulevard transit. It was noticeably cleaner than most, and quiet too. Not only were fewer people using the booths, but there was little noise coming from the street. The usual hum of city was muted here.
> teleport
Choose a destination
 - Bureau Street

 - - - Vic typed in the code for his destination, and an instant later was in a booth at Bureau Street.

Bureau Street TeleMat Station

 - - - The TeleMat station for the main administration area, this was one of the largest in the city, and at rush hour it would be a seething mass of people. Right now, it was relatively quiet.
> w

Bureau Street

 - - - Vic stood in Bureau Street and looked about. This was where much of the administration of New Chicago was, including the police station, right across from the TeleMat station, to the west. To the right of the police station, there was a bar, "Donegal's Authentic Irish Bar"; that was where Vic was most likely to find Detective Munroe. A temporary stall had been set up beside the TeleMat station by some enterprising guy by the name of Pierre, offering flowers for the busy office workers to take home to their loved ones.

 - - - A Ya-Po hovered by in its enviro-tank.
> ask pierre about flowers

 - - - "Say, what flowers do you recommend for a guy going on a date with a girl for the first time?" asked Vic.

 - - - "You cannot go wrong with roses, my friend, but lilies will be appreciated too, and might look more thoughful. It's 3 credits either way."
> buy lilies

 - - - Vic bought a bunch of lilies for 5 credits.
> nw

Donegal's Authentic Irish Bar

 - - - As Vic surveyed Donegal's Irish Bar, he wondered just how authentic this place was. Would a real Irish pub have shamrock shaped tables, and videos of "Riverdance" on every available wall? The customers were a mix of business men and cops; even those who were not in suits or uniform looked to be plainclothes cops to Vic's experienced eye. As expected, Munroe was here, his old partner from his brief time as a cop.
> ask munroe about lawrence devalle

 - - - "So what can you tell me about about Lawrence DeValle," asked Vic.

 - - - "He was found dead just after seven thirty A.M. by the housekeeper. Shot in the chest, with something designed to be as messy as possible. I'm betting on a YP-33. From the wound, we can know he was shot several times from somewhere near the bottom of the stairs, while he was stood facing that way, half way between there and the door."
> ask munroe about maisy devalle

 - - - "So what do you know about Maisy DeValle," Vic asked casually.

 - - - Jill gave him a look. "Is this about a case, Vic? You do know we have an APB out on her. If you knew where she was, you would tell me, right?"

 - - - "I was just curious, what with it being in the papers. So what about her?"

 - - - "Well, all the evidence's against her. She stands to inherit a ton, and we know she was at the house when her husband died, and she did a runner after the murder. Still waiting for the forenics, but she's as good as fried."
> give cigarette to munroe

 - - - "I found this near the DeValle place." Vic handed the cigarette end, still in the evidence bag, to Jill. "You might want to get your boys to take a look at it."

 - - - "Where exactly did you find this?"

 - - - "On the wall round the mansion. I figure the guy climbed a tree, then smoked this while watching the house."
> ask munroe about telemat logs

 - - - "What's the latest on the DeValle case? Have the TeleMat records turned up anything?" In theory, the records could pinpoint exactly who when where at any time; the system did record each person going through in absolute detail to reproduce him or her at the other end. However, Old Earth privacy laws meant that it was illegal for the TeleMat system to store identifying data for more than a fraction of a second. Nevertheless, Opulent Boulevard was not well used, and it would at least be interesting to know where people went to and from the the relevant time, even if he did not know who it was.

 - - - "You know I'm not supposed to tell you."

 - - - "But you're going to anyway."

 - - - She smiled. "Two guys arrived at Opulent Street from Twenty Third Avenue separately in the early hours. Later one goes back. Here is the mystery; shortly after that a Uralgan goes to Grand Hotel, but we can see no sign of him on the security cameras at either end. Oh, and you never heard any of that from me, okay?."

 - - - "You're a sweetheart, Jill."

 - - - "I'm an idiot, Vic."
> se

Bureau Street

 - - - Vic stood in Bureau Street and looked about. This was where much of the administration of New Chicago was, including the police station, right across from the TeleMat station, to the west. To the right of the police station, there was a bar, "Donegal's Authentic Irish Bar"; that was where Vic was most likely to find Detective Munroe. A temporary stall had been set up beside the TeleMat station by some enterprising guy by the name of Pierre, offering flowers for the busy office workers to take home to their loved ones.
> e

