Choose a destination
 - Yardley Street

 - - - Vic typed in the code for his destination, and an instant later was in a booth at Yardley Street.

Yardley Street TeleMat Station

 - - - Vic looked about Yardley Street Telemat Station. It was typical of many such stations across New Chicago. Larger than most, it had twenty four booths along three walls; fourteen were for departing, ten for arriving. As he wondered where to go next, a stream of people passed through.
> n

Yardley Street

 - - - Vic was now in the middle of Yardley Street, near the transit station, which was on the south side of the street. Shops and other businesses lined the street. Numerous people were out, hurrying about their business, or just enjoying the fine weather.
> w

Yardley Street (West)

 - - - The west end of Yardley Street had a style all of its own. In this part of the city, the area had a certain reputation for its bars and restaurants, such as Piggy Sue's, to the north, and L'Escargots, to the south. Of the two, Piggy Sue's was Vic's kind of place.

 - - - A group of Jonto-monks walked by, quietly muttering incantations to keep themselves ritually clean as they mingled with the heathens.
> s

L'Escargot's (Lobby)

 - - - The lobby was small. Curtains prevented Vic from seeing into the actual restaurant, but there was a menu on the wall, and a wonderful aroma of garlic, coriander and oregano. The food sounded great, but there were no prices, which Vic took to be a bad sign. The owner, Maurice Chapeau, claimed to be French born, but Vic had his doubts. Very, very few people in New Chicago had even visited Earth. Needless to say, Vic had never actually eaten here before.
> e

 - - - "Do you 'ave a reservation, monsieur?"

 - - - For once, Vic did. "Sure, in the name Linda Love."

 - - - "Ah, bon. Please, this way, monsieur. Mademoiselle is waiting for you."

L'Escargot's

 - - - L'Escargot's was one fancy restaurant; Vic was impressed that Linda Love had got a reservation for them. There were about a dozen tables, all set for two, each with a deep red table cloth, and a candle. In fact the twelve candles were about the only illumination, and it took Vic a few moments to spot Linda, sat at a table to the right. She smiled at him, as he sat down in the chair opposite her.
> look at linda love

 - - - She certainly scrubbed up well, Vic thought. Linda was dressed in a very short red dress, and Vic could see she had a great set on pins on her. The perfume that had before smelled cheap, now smelled heady and erotic.
> give lilies to linda

 - - - Vic handed the lilies he had bought to Linda, and her face lit up. "Hey, that's so thoughful, Vic. Lilies are so beautful; you're so sensitive! So much nicer than the usual guys I date, who are only after one thing."
> tell linda about myself

 - - - "Tell me about Vic Gantry," said Linda.

 - - - "Well, I didn't do too well at school, so when a couple of guys said they were going to be cops, I figured I might do the same. After three years of training, and over a year on the job, I decided I was not the sort of guy that likes to take orders, so I set up my own business as a P.I. Been doing that ever since."
> ask linda about herself

 - - - "So tell me about yourself," said Vic.

 - - - "There's not much to tell. I'm a bit of a geek, to be honest. Good grades at school, got a job as a software engineer with SynCorp." She leant forward, inadventedly letting Vic ee down her dress. "A few months ago, I decided to go freelance; I had some ideas about better encyption software... I'm not boring you am I?"

 - - - Vic hastily looked up from her cleavage. "No, absolutely not. Go on."

 - - - "The problem with data encryption..." She continued for some time, but Vic was not really paying attention to what she said.
> ask linda about encryption

 - - - "If I had a little problem with some encrypted files, you'd be able to help me I guess."

 - - - Linda shrugged. "I expect so. But let's leave that until tomorrow. I really don't want to tak about work now."
> w

 - - - Vic had to admit the food was great. So was the wine. "That was a great meal," he said as he was presented with the bill. At 230 credits, it had better be; he would not be back here in a while.

 - - - "I had a really good time tonight, Vic. Would you... like to come back to my place for coffee? My apartment's in the building across the road."

Linda Love's Apartment

 - - - Linda's apartment was small, but well kept. A living room, with kitchen area in one corner; a large sofa was the only large piece of furniture, facing the TV screen on the wall. Beyond that a bedroom, with a tiny bathroom attached. The door was south.

 - - - "Sure, that would be great," said Vic, trying not to sound too keen. The bill paid, Linda took his hand, and they walked to her apartment.
> look at linda love

 - - - Linda looked wonderful as she smiled demurly in her very short red dress. Vic admired her long legs, now she was barefoot, and inhaled her heady perfume. "You're one good-looking babe, Linda." She smiled at the compliment.
> make love to linda

 - - - Vic took Linda in his arms, picking her up, and carrying her to the small bed...
> s

 - - - Later, Vic had to accept he really needed to get on with the case. "This has been great, perhaps we could do it again some time."

 - - - "That would be nice," smiled Linda. She kissed him good bye, and he left her apartment, heading down to the street.

