Choose a destination
 - New Chicago University

 - - - Vic typed in the code for his destination, and an instant later was in a booth at New Chicago University.

NCU TeleMat station

 - - - The NCU TeleMat Station was like no other. Generations of students had left their marks, whether sanctioned by the university or not, so the walls were a riot of colour. To Vic's eye, it was just a mess, but doubtless it meant something to someone at the university. Whether that was someone in the fine arts department or the anthropology department, Vic was not too sure. The university was off to the east.
> e

NPC Campus

 - - - The central campus of the CYU was a large grassed area, crossed with gravel paths, and surrounded by the various departmental buildings. The lawn was littered with students, studying, chatting, drinking or kissing. A signpost pointed northeast to the History and Archaeology Department, and west back to the TeleMat station.

 - - - The History and Archaeology Department was a hexagonal building, each side of which was displaying an animated sequence from Uralgas past, or possibly earlier than that. Vic's history was a bit shaky, but he certainly recognised the Tequila Riots of '84.
> ne

Dept History and Archaeology (Lobby)

 - - - The foyer of the History and Archaeology Department was grand and imposing. A series of free standing pillars contained holograms of historical events. Posters on the wall proclaimed forth-coming events, many that had long since happened, Vic noted. Stairs led up to the lecture halls, while a sign to the north east indicated the laboratory lay that way. There were offices; to the north, Prof Kant's, and to the west, Dr. Lancing's. A secretary, Una, sat at a desk. The building exit was though large glass doors to the southwest.
> ask una about lancing

 - - - "Hi," said Vic. "I was wondering if I could talk to Dr Lancing."

 - - - "I'm afraid Dr Lancing is currently unavailable."

 - - - "Do you know when he will be available."

 - - - "Huh! Like he would bother to tell me what his plans are. I'm just his secretary."
> ask una about kant

 - - - "Well could I talk to Prof Kant?"

 - - - "Do you have an appointment?"

 - - - "Not as such..."

 - - - "Not as such?... Look, I shouldn't do this, and she has a seminar in five minutes, but if it is quick, just knock on the door.
> knock

 - - - Vic knocked twice on the door, heard a "Come in", and walked into Prof Kant's office.

Prof Kant's office

 - - - Prof Kant's office was small and functional; somehow Vic had expected something more fancy for an academic. The entire west wall was covered with newspaper printouts. Prof Kant was sat at a desk; she looked up from her computer.
> ask kant about lancing

 - - - "Thank you for seeing me, professor," said Vic. "I'm working on a case, and I was hoping to talking to Dr. Lancing about an artefact he found..."

 - - - "Mr..?"

 - - - "Gantry. Vic Gantry."

 - - - "My Gantry, Dr Lancing collects a great many artefacts; you would have to talk to him about it. And I really have no idea where he might be." This was getting him nowhere fast, Vic realised. He needed some way to connect to her, so she might be prepared to trust him at least a little.
> look at clippings

 - - - Vic briefly scanned the wall of clippings; they seemed to be events that had occurred in New Chicago in the last fifteen years or so. One in particular caught his eye. "Pentown Bombing: Man Arrested" It was a case Vic had been involved in, and he knew for a fact the papers had got it all wrong.

 - - - Professor Kant noticed what Vic was reading. "I like to keep a visual record of recent history as a reminder to students that what happens today is history tomorrow. That article has some personal interest for me."
> ask kant about pentown

 - - - "I worked on that case," said Vic, "it was just as I was starting out as a P.I."

 - - - "The man they arrested was innocent! He was acquitted at trial, thank goodness, but it was such an ordeal. He's my brother."

 - - - "Of course! Clive Kant, that was his name. The cops were all for sending him to the chair, until the real bomber was found."

 - - - "You did that?" Suddenly she seemed rather more friendly to Vic.

 - - - "Well, I helped find him, sure. It's a similar deal now, Professor. A woman is set to be fried unless I can help her."
> ask kant about lancing

 - - - "So about Dr Lancing?"

 - - - "As I said, I don't know where he is, though I suppose you might like to look in on his apartment. It's on the ground floor of Jonti Building, on the south side of the campus green."
> s

