Choose a destination
 - Twenty Third Avenue

 - - - Vic typed in the code for his destination, and an instant later was in a booth at Twenty Third Avenue.

Twenty Third Avenue TeleMat Station

 - - - This was the Twenty Third Avenue TeleMat station. One of the larger ones, and one a guy would avoid if he could help it. The smell of cigarettes and urine, the discarded litter of ten thousand people a day, not to mention the risk of mugging from any number of desperate lowlifes. Even the AutoCleans feared to come here.

 - - - The TeleMat station for perhaps the worst part of the city. Not a place to hang around. Not if you wanted to keep your wallet and your liver. But Vic knew the place, and hopefully knew how to keep out of trouble. He had a contact here, Mickey Singh; talking to him might be a good idea. He usually hung out at Topside, one of many seedy bars in the area.
> w

 - - - As Vic left the TeleMat station, he wondered why it was that every investigation brought him back here. Twenty Third was home to some of the worst scum in New Chicago, and some of its most lively entertainments. Just coming here was gambling that you would be alive the next day.

Twenty Third Avenue

 - - - Vic looked up and down Twenty Third Avenue. It was busy, but then it was always business. Most street corners had a hooker or two touting for business, and the shops were all offering sex or gambling or some either vice, or were just boarded shut. He did not know why, but the steeet always seemed to have more than the usual number of Uralgans.

 - - - In a shop doorway, two lovers embraced. They could be no more than fourteen, thought Vic, shaking his head.
> se

Topside Bar

 - - - Topside bar was squeezed between a closed-down food store and a brothel. Inside was more like a wide corridor than a room, it was dark, and smelt of damp; Vic could not imagine why people would come here, but nevertheless there were several people sat at the bar, even at this time of day. All seemed to be drinking alone. He spotted Mickey Singh towards the back of the room.
> ask mickey about yp-33

 - - - "Mickey, you know anyone who hangs out on Twenty Third uses a YP-33?"

 - - - "Funny, I can't remember. Can't remember much at the minute, Mr G."
> give cash to mickey

 - - - "I wonder if I can give you a few credits to jog your memory about a few things." Vic took 50 credits off his credit chip, and transferred them to Mickey's.

 - - - "Much obliged, Mr G. Always a pleasure to help you any way I can."
> ask mickey about yp-33

 - - - "Mickey, you know anyone who hangs out on Twenty Third uses a YP-33?"

 - - - "A YP-33, eh? There's no one round here uses them any more, Mr. G... No one except Bram Fenton, that is. One of Nikki Stom's boys. None too bright either. Well, if he was bright, he wouldn't use a YP-33, not with their history."
> ask mickey about fenton

 - - - "What do yu know about Bram Fenton, Mickey?"

 - - - "Fenton's basically a petty crook, you know, picking pocket, house breaking. Not a violent guy, generally, not none too bright either. Stom pretty much looks after him."
> ask mickey about myothian falcon

 - - - "Ever heard of something called the Myothian Falcon.

 - - - A shake of the head. "Nope."
> nw

Twenty Third Avenue

 - - - Vic looked up and down Twenty Third Avenue. It was busy, but then it was always business. Most street corners had a hooker or two touting for business, and the shops were all offering sex or gambling or some either vice, or were just boarded shut. He did not know why, but the steeet always seemed to have more than the usual number of Uralgans.
> w

Green Heaven

 - - - The Green Heaven... Vic had never noticed the place before. Clearly it catered to guys with unusual tastes. The clientele was strictly male and human, the entertainment was female and green. For a moment, Vic watched the two Uralgan girls gyrating naked on the stage, before taking in the rest of the place. About a dozen men were watching the dancers, entranced. To the south, a third Uralgan was serving drinks; this one, Syrella, was at least wearing something. To the east, the door back to the street.
> look at dancers

 - - - Vic took a few more minutes to look at the two dancers, purely to see how much like humans they were. Their skin was an emerald green, their eyes were green too, but darker; but the shape of their bodies was like that of a human woman - and a well-stacked on at that, Vic reckoned. They were lithe and agile dancers too, and Vic could almost see why men came here to watch them.
> ask syrella about myothian falcon

 - - - "Say, you won't have heard of something called the Myothian Falcon, have you?"

 - - - Syrella shook her head. "No. You might want to Lairas; she's from the Myothi nation originally. Might mean something to her. She'll be in the back; I'll make sure they let you through."
> s

Green Heaven (Back Stage)

 - - - The back stage area was basically a single small room, with places where the girls could get changed and put on make-up. There was just one Uralgan girl there at the moment, sat at a mirror, preparing for her act. Presumably, this was Lairas.
> ask lairas about myothian falcon

 - - - "I'm looking for a couple of Uralgans recently here from Myothi. You seen anyone like that?"

 - - - "Yeah, I seen them. A guy, Kalal, and, well, I think she might be a preistess, Erida-Pa. I've kind of lost touch with the old ways. I think they're living in a derelict clothing shop a little way south down the avenue."
> ask lairas about uralgans

 - - - "I'm looking for a couple of Uralgans recently here from Myothi. You seen anyone like that?"

 - - - "Yeah, I seen them. A guy, Kalal, and, well, I think she might be a preistess, Erida-Pa. I've kind of lost touch with the old ways. I think they're living in a derelict clothing shop a little way south down the avenue."
