Twenty Third Avenue TeleMat Station

 - - - This was the Twenty Third Avenue TeleMat station. One of the larger ones, and one a guy would avoid if he could help it. The smell of cigarettes and urine, the discarded litter of ten thousand people a day, not to mention the risk of mugging from any number of desperate lowlifes. Even the AutoCleans feared to come here.
> use telemat booth
Choose a destination
 - Bureau Street

 - - - Vic typed in the code for his destination, and an instant later was in a booth at Bureau Street.

Bureau Street TeleMat Station

 - - - The TeleMat station for the main administration area, this was one of the largest in the city, and at rush hour it would be a seething mass of people. Right now, it was relatively quiet.
> w

Bureau Street

 - - - Vic stood in Bureau Street and looked about. This was where much of the administration of New Chicago was, including the police station, right across from the TeleMat station, to the west. To the right of the police station, there was a bar, "Donegal's Authentic Irish Bar"; that was where Vic was most likely to find Detective Munroe. A temporary stall had been set up beside the TeleMat station by some enterprising guy by the name of Pierre, offering flowers for the busy office workers to take home to their loved ones.
> nw

Donegal's Authentic Irish Bar

 - - - As Vic surveyed Donegal's Irish Bar, he wondered just how authentic this place was. Would a real Irish pub have shamrock shaped tables, and videos of "Riverdance" on every available wall? The customers were a mix of business men and cops; even those who were not in suits or uniform looked to be plainclothes cops to Vic's experienced eye. As expected, Munroe was here, his old partner from his brief time as a cop.
> ask jill about cigarette

 - - - "Your boys found anything on that cigarette end yet, Jill?"

 - - - "Yeah. Alway good for forensics, a used cigarette. It was smoked by a guy caled Bram Fenton. Quite a history, but petty stuff mostly. Nothing violent."
> tell jill about fenton

 - - - "Jill, I know who murdered Lawrence DeValle, and it wasn't his wife."

 - - - "I'm listening."

 - - - "It was that lowlife Bram Fenton, whose cigarette end your boys analysed. He's also about the only guy in New Chicago packing a YP-33, the weapon used to murder DeValle."

 - - - "Okay, that fits. But you need to explain why he did it. And how he turned off the fancy security system. Neither fit the profile for Fenton."

 - - - "Fenton was there to steal something, a statuette called the Myothian Falcon."

 - - - "Okay, well that is more Fenton's style than murder, so that makes sense. But even if he was caught, Fenton's just not the killing type. That stupid gun of his is just for show."

 - - - "This is where it gets weird. This Myothian Falcon has some kind of psychotropic effect, on guys anyway. When he picked it up, he saw DeValle as a terrible monster - that is what he shot."

 - - - "Are you serious?"

 - - - "Absolutely. It affected Lancing when he first picked it up, it affected me too."

 - - - "That sounds like a temporary insanity plea in the making. So let's say that did happen, it still leaves the security system. I know Fenton; he's barely able to turn a light off, let alone an expensive security system."

 - - - "Fenton didn't turn off the security system, DeValle did. He had spent the night with his Uralgan mistress, and turned off the security system so his wife wouldn't be any the wiser."

 - - - "A guy like DeValle with a Uralgan? Doesn't sound too likely."

 - - - "Oh, DeValle was big on Uralgan girls. He was quite a regular at the Green Heaven Club."

 - - - "You know, that makes a twisted kind of sense. Did you know Maisy was a Uralgan? The TeleMat logs had two people go to to the house, DeValle, and later the killer. Then two leave, one a Uralgan. The killer, and then Mrs DeValle it turns out. She must've done gene therapy of something so her skins not green, and stuck on a wig.

 - - - "You know what, Vic? I think you've solved the case. Maisy DeValle should be very grateful; you can leave Fenton to us."
unlocked
> se

